[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating coverage instrumentation**\n\nI’m trying to figure out coverage instrumentation. It seems that the appended jar shouldn’t be the original if it’s not instrumented. Also, a custom classloader might define a Locator with a null parent, but it shouldn't be bootstrap. There’s definitely some confusion around this, and I’ve got to clarify what’s happening with the jars and classloader. This feels a bit complex, but I'm working through it!\n\n**Evaluating test structure**\n\nI need to create a dedicated LocatorTest that will include tests for class$ and resource getResource. It seems I should keep a public top-level structure for the tests. I'm considering whether to remove the existing Ant_launcherTest placeholder or just leave it as is. The rules suggest a one-to-one mapping, but I need to decide if I can edit the placeholder or repurpose it for general APIs, given the coverage requirements. Should I make the test classes public to adhere to rules?\n\n**Revising test class structure**\n\nI see the need to ensure the active class is public, which the existing top-level violates, so I should fix that. I could place tests in the existing file, but the name Ant_launcherTest doesn’t match the active class, making it confusing. Creating a LocatorTest.java makes sense to avoid scaffold-only issues. I plan to use assertj for assertions and ensure that my JUnit methods are package-private. \n\nThe first test will check if a null loader falls back correctly, while another will verify that a resource from the Launcher class returns the expected results.\n\n**Considering URI API tests**\n\nI'm thinking about testing the URI APIs, but it seems I can focus on the active class instead of dynamic ones. Having just one test might suffice, as long as it provides high coverage. I could test `getClassSource(Locator.class)` to see if it returns correctly in native scenarios, but it appears that resources might not be available. Maybe I could just use a non-existing resource to see how it behaves? That could make for an interesting test!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_04563a74adf902b50169f6db362274819e94d128ec7a1a6318\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9ttItb8m1v9647L26G8pWU0dRQ1WheI84HhLTAo9iFT3wMU4qP_82wCwlvB9irpOV-h9DJBJJeG5ilGqLN7UjFwmtkoNHN9q-AtM2SzWCQJVZre3nL-LSs4WFEDdGzVQQ71AarTTpTpodFJxgX6mXuLgHYjxqljVlZZQbxcElmTQ-f8JHC91X0YBmQezIkWkUtSCmGSh4TDiNxrYsVK4ZvveTI1Skbr0SkDnf3VJmLBDyf9etVRMeG1JAFVQiI-W0zmm_3ihUSl_bM2e8eGEuI_BUYKCMUNTiSbDrhuTYBBy4nP3azWdV6_alSfd508S1LCNp0CXbjz9nS8NRWIAAnqf80HbIe0Otn_uueFwEV_V9ZdCMr-jpuve7yjC_Pc4WC-szP89X1EZsh8KEsE_NaB5-4ScSwoZEXz2Wz2pA8srT0veDsAbl1Hp8pqf7Zt1aUt2Jaf3ViPmQdHKxEUWi8XIAgTDGEyHpZk8S9BbvapgYneT4HcRgqwFgzCWEs8CE8-QzW-Lmc4JwPK8gI7aGdyi8heL0dMY_b--kVQTeU3UOSbAMsm0h-G5ZepAUOQ8JiDR78-nb7VSof1V_qusOLtWk9-hd1btMLgsKcd60HoIm-kwvsD1GRYSp3GY4U0MWxccMbo9D3NaiHYYtZ9LNaTE51jYIQxPxw_nnUOT1T6qzkzhs8xvRRxPoroHUNdnggDaB-fEM1G4O3_2m-XinI3SABihm8neUbCJ4HUkqZYkACfRHqrBia5ya4GV9RVHO8ITqASsIjrixqdUcLCrXay564SS9W1pKe2vSGxbsQ7gTIU1E2R16GOy9umtD06ZpJUnCnOmskt4xk42TsrOiEk2W0jHkNTmZFgqR0hHijBn2SEsEWljusWrb4InGV0jyAx1uaV1LZ4GkkG2WQY7lcNVGes15Qf4FKEHDd9U5yUapN2EtDMM1Op3xjiz1ktc-y-zkW5js4y4DHJxSyZkCOJ79UBFi2QOrFusxBn7fSikzL40OajGYzz36-e8rW_K1A3L7NqolxkqBBWrj28FxFavjDcn-ugeuQW6XSP9uK-AMKxS3fEjcRBe3mWTNMhDt711v90TBUbWiX4RmcC750AuegonsiFgofUZ01SArngW6eKO4z3T6-ZJdCDWT2ruDKK6WoIRZvokb41BCalCQTZM1r2vkycGSPYyCTokh1DhFV3_mKRRXT_97R03qVdnZH1AlirdRD5q_yGYLRiJ-JCcXxWRYR8TMUfPtUHcGE8GtFZUZatCsMn6yBcIy-Fg6852JE-zXeNCuhgtT_xGFqVxSMziWOvneQLVS89W75oFwi_FXwWIig-z0BGzbX35VFRVtW-wtgOP0CXkzKIKlrVVVxrAttH5_QEssGl1U67TLnDcg_SBltQi4yr95j6yvuQ05GlhnF_uRwyisIvHXFdG_2mKzrOeOj7U_JLTzeOT1YGSa66kWhN8UE0BrBAUxz-XiU9-4vHlQ2l3KLMJs5AoatJ50dJ0fXssq4jFZsOOXlW9KHvTokh3oXQv3ZUQTnez5ucfoKxlY0G8OdLqB2qqrkdBz6efTtrzr9rmuBWeHbf--C8Te8MARExghQ0rqBxau933YUu94H42-Lx7fCZbv-hPtvmSHTENTwUIgplYHj6joW6ZX4o8xKVmq0jyNXTe0T-JNdUMtaxLBkttapg